paint_information_ge(19,'Hundertwasser lived from 1949 on as a guest of the family Dumage who resided in St. Mand&Atilde;&copy; in the former hunting-castle of the countess Castiglione, a lover of Napoleon III. The mural was painted on a brick wall in the second floor. In 1954 the painting was viewed by Dorival Dominguez and Marie Laure de Noailles. The castle was pulled down in 1964. The painting was then dismantled together with its brick wall, sawed up into 13 irregular pieces by Riccardo Licata and stored in Basel. In freight containers it was shipped to Long Island, where it was joined together again by Licata in the reformed Synagogue, an old Romanesque castle. In 2007 the painting was dismantled again together with its brick wall, but in one piece and removed from the synagogue. Since then it is in private possession.').
